<ce:para>MgH<inf>2</inf> is a light-weight metal hydride having a hydrogen storage capacity of 7.7 wt %. Theoretical calculations that model the first steps of the hydrogenation of Mg<inf>2</inf>Si are performed to understand why ball milling is required to hydrogenate Mg<inf>2</inf>Si. Electronic density functional theory calculations were used to investigate the adsorption and dissociation of H<inf>2</inf> on the clean and oxidized Mg<inf>2</inf>Si surfaces. The (-110) surface was the most energetically favorable among all the surfaces tested. The adsorption energies were calculated for H atoms and H<inf>2</inf> molecules on the surface to identify the most favorable binding sites and geometries. The energy barriers for hydrogen dissociation on the clean Mg<inf>2</inf>Si surface along two different pathways were computed. The energy barrier for hydrogen dissociation on the surface with 2/3 ML coverage of oxygen increased to 80 kJ/mole. There were no energetically favorable sites for hydrogen atoms to adsorb when the oxygen coverage was â‰¥ 5/4 ML, indicating that hydrogen can not dissociate on oxidized Mg<inf>2</inf>Si surfaces. Oxide formation on the Mg<inf>2</inf>Si surface was highly exothermic, having an energy of about 4.5 eV per oxygen atom. The pure Mg<inf>2</inf>Si surface was expected to be highly reactive to oxidation. Hydrogen decomposition should be facile on the clean Mg<inf>2</inf>Si surface at room temperature, but that surface oxidation will prevent dissociation under ambient conditions. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the 2006 AIChE National Meeting (San Francisco, CA 11/12-17/2006).</ce:para>
